    <title>Linear Algebra and Differential Equations</title>
    <subtitle></subtitle>

    <!-- Include frontmatter -->
    <xi:include href="./frontmatter.ptx" />

        <chapter>
      <title>Introduction to Differential Equations</title>
      <section>
        <title>Mathematical Modeling</title>
        <p>
          Differential equations (DEs) are used to mathematically model physical situations. The first example of using a differential equation to model real world situations is Newton's 2nd Law.
          <md>
            {\bf F}=m{\bf a}=m\frac{d^2{\bf r}}{dt^2}
          </md>
          Some other examples of differential equation models that you are probably familiar with.
          <p>
          <alert>Radioactive decay :</alert> The rate of decay of a radioactive substance is proportional to the amount of the substance.
          <md>
            \frac{dA}{dt}=-kA
          </md>
          with solution
          <md>
            A(t)=A(0)e^{-kt}
          </md>
          </p>
          <p>
          <alert>Projectiles :</alert> Motion of a particle under constant gravitational acceleration downwards
          <md>
            {\bf r}''=-g{\bf j}
          </md>
          with solution
          <md>
            {\bf r}={\bf r}(0)+{\bf v}(0)t-\frac{1}{2}gt^2{\bf j}
          </md>
          </p>
          <p>
          <alert>Newton's Law of Cooling :</alert> The rate of change of the temperature of an object is proportional to the difference between its temperature and the temperature of its surroundings.
          <md>
            \frac{dT}{dt}=-k(T-T_s)
          </md>
          with solution
          <md>
            T(t)=T_s+ce^{-kt}
          </md>
          </p>
          <p>
          <alert>Population :</alert> The rate of change of a population is proportional to the population.
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt}=rP
          </md>
          with solution
          <md>
            p(t)=p(0)e^{kt}
          </md>
          </p>
          <p>
          <alert> Logistic Population Model :</alert>
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt}=rp\left(1-\frac{p}{m}\right)
          </md>
          with solution
          <md>
            p(t)=\frac{m}{1+ce^{-rt}}
          </md>
          </p>
          
        </p>
        
      </section>
      <section>
        <title>Ordinary Differential equations</title>
        <p>
          An ordinary differential equation consists of a real dependent variable, a real independent variable, and derivatives of the dependent variable with respect to the independent variable. It can be expressed in the implicit form.
          <md>
            f(t,y,y',\cdots,y^{(n)}=0
          </md>
          where <m>y</m> is the dependent variable and <m>t</m> is the independent variable. The normal form is obtained by solving for the highest derivative (if possible).
          <md>
            y{(n)}=g(t,y,y',\cdots,y^{(n-1)})
          </md>
          <p>
            The order of a differential equation is the order of the highest derivative. The examples in the previous section were all first order except the projectile example.
          </p>
          <p>
            A differential equation is linear if it is a linear function of the dependent variable and its derivatives. Otherwise it is nonlinear. All of the examples in the previous section are linear except for the Logistic model.
          </p>
          <p>
            A differential equation is autonomous if the independent variable doesn't appear explicitly in the equation. All of the examples in the previous section are autonomous.
          </p>
        </p>
        <p>
          Here are some more complicated differential equation models
          <p>
            <alert>The Van der Pol equation :</alert> It describes the current in a certain type of electrical circuit.
            <md>
              \frac{d^2i}{dt^2}-\mu(1-i^2)\frac{di}{dt}+i=0
            </md>
            The dependent variable is <m>i</m> and the independent variable is <m>t</m>. It is second order, nonlinear, and autonomous
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>The Euler-Bernoulli equation :</alert> It describes the the deflection of a beam
            <md>
              \frac{d^2}{dx^2}\left(EI\frac{d^2y}{dx^2}\right)=q(x)
            </md>
            The dependent variable is <m>y</m> the independent variable is <m>x</m>. It is fourth order, linear and it isn't autonomous
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>The Schrodinger equation for the hydrogen atom</alert>
            <md>
              \frac{1}{r^2}\frac{d}{dr}\left(r^2\frac{d\psi}{dr}\right)+\left(E+\frac{k}{r}\right)\psi=0
            </md>
            The dependent variable is <m>\psi</m> and the independent variable is <m>r</m>. It is second order, linear and not autonomous,
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>The Blasius equation</alert> It describes boundary layer flow of a fluid over a flat plate.
            <md>
              f'''+\frac{1}{2}f\,f''=0'
            </md>
            The dependent variable is <m>f</m>, the independent variable isn't given explicitly. The equation is third order, nonlinear, and autonomous
          </p>
        </p>
        
      </section>
      <section xml:id="sec-Solutions">
        <title>Solutions</title>
        <p>
          An analytic or closed form solution to a differential equation is an expression relating the dependent and independent variables without derivatives, which when differentiated makes the differential equation an identity. Solutions can given in explicit form <m>y=f(t)</m> or in implicit form <m>g(y,t)=\text{constant}</m>
        </p>
        <subsection>
          <title>Analytic solutions in explicit form</title>
          <p>
            If the differential equation is
            <md>
              y'=f(t,y)
            </md>
            then an explicit solution <m>y=g(t)</m> of the equation makes
            <md>
              g'(t)=f(t,g(t))
            </md>
            an identity
          </p>
          <example>
            <statement>
              <p>
                The differential equation
                <md>
                  y'=-\frac{3}{t}\,y+6t^2
                </md>
                has a solution <m>y=t^3</m> since
                <md>
                  (t^3)'=-\frac{3t^3}{t}+6t^2 \quad\Rightarrow\quad 3t^2=-3t^2+6t^2
                </md>
                So it satisfies the equation. <m>y=t^3</m> is called a particular solution. The general solution to the equation is
                <md>
                  y=t^3+\frac{c}{t^3}
                </md>
                where <m>c</m> is an arbitrary constant analogous to the <m>+C</m> when finding antiderivatives
              </p>
            </statement>
          </example>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
          <title>Analytic solutions in implicit form</title>
          <p>
            To check whether an implicit function <m>g(t,y)=\text{constant}</m> satisfies a differential equation
            <md>
              y'=f(t,y)
            </md>
            we have to implicitly differentiate the function and solve for <m>y'</m>
            <md>
              \frac{d}{dt}(g(t,y))=\partial_t g +\partial_y g\, y'=0 \quad\Rightarrow\quad y'=-\frac{g_t}{g_y}
            </md>
            <m>g_t,g_y</m> are the partial derivatives of g, that is they are the usual derivatives with respect to the variable while considering all the other variables to be constant. The function will be a solution to the equation if
            <md>
              -\frac{g_t}{g_y}=f(t,y)
            </md>
            
          </p>
          <example>
            <p>
              A closed form solution to the differential equation
              <md>
                y'=-\frac{\cos y+2ty}{-t\sin y+t^2+3y^2}
              </md>
              is given by <m>g(t,y)=t\cos y+t^2y+y^3=c</m> since
              <md>
                \partial_t g=\cos y+2ty\qquad \partial_y g=-t\sin y+t^2+3y^2
              </md>
              and
              <md>
                -\frac{g_t}{g_y}=-\frac{\cos y+2ty}{-t\sin y+t^2+3y^2}=f(t,y)
              </md>
              
            </p>
          </example>
        </subsection>
      </section>
      <section>
        <title>Initial Value Problems</title>
        <p>
          In applications of differential equations we are usually interested in finding solutions that satisfy another requirement called an initial condition. This has the effect of fixing the arbitrary constant in the general solution.
        </p>
        <p>
          An initial value problem (IVP) consists of a differential equations together with a given initial value of the dependent variable.
          <md>
            y'=f(t,y) \qquad y(t_0)=y_0
          </md>
          If we are using the IVP to model a physical situation, we want the solution to make sense. The mathematical issues that need to be addressed are
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
              <alert>Existence :</alert> Does the solution exist?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <alert>Uniqueness :</alert> If a solution exists, is it unique?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <alert>Interval of existence :</alert> If a unique solution is found. For what values of the independent variable is the solution valid?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <subsection>
          <title>What can go wrong?</title>
          <p>
            <alert>Existence</alert> Just as in the theory of algebraic equations, we are not guaranteed a solution to a given IVP. Sometimes it is clear the a solution cannot exist. For example. consider the IVP
            <md>
              y'=4ty\ln(1-2t)\qquad y(1)=3
            </md>
            since substituting the initial condition into the right hand side of the equation implies <m>y'(1)</m> is undefined
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>Uniqueness</alert> Sometimes there is more than one solution to a given IVP. Consider
            <md>
              y'=\frac{2(y-1)}{t}\qquad y(0)=1
            </md>
            This has solutions of the form
            <md>
              y=1+ct^2
            </md>
            with <m>c</m> arbitrary.
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>Interval of existence</alert> For some differential equations the interval of existence will depend on the initial conditions. The IVP
            <md>
              ty'+\sqrt{t+4}y^2=\frac{e^t}{(x-3)^2}
            </md>
            The differential equation is undefined for <m>t\ln-4,t=0,t=3</m>, so depending on the position of the initial condition the possible intervals of existence are <m>([-4,0),(0,3),(3,\infty)</m>. A subtler problem occurs when the solution of the differential equation has a singularity. As an example the IVP
            <md>
              y'=1+y^2 \qquad y(3)=1
            </md>
            has the solution
            <md>
              y=\tan\left(t-3+\frac{\pi}{4}\right)\qquad \frac{\pi}{2}\leq t\leq \frac{3\pi}{2}
            </md>
            since <m>\tan</m> has vertical asymptotes at odd multiple of <m>\pi/2</m>
          </p>
        </subsection>
      </section>
      <section>
        <title>An Existence and Uniqueness Theorem</title>
        <theorem xml:id="thm-">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Given the initial value problem
              <md>
                y'=f(t,y)\qquad y(t_0)=y_0
              </md>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If <m>f(t,y)</m> is continuous in the open rectangle <m>a\t t\lt b,c\lt y \lt d</m> then the IVP has a solution in an open interval <m>a\lt \alpha\lt t\lt \beta\lt b</m> about the initial point <m>(t_0,y_0)</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If in addition the partial derivative <m>f_y</m> is also continuous the solution is unique.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
              Notes
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The theorem is a local existence theorem. It only guarantees a solution in a neighborhood of the initial point. It doesn't give any information about the interval of existence.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The theorem gives sufficient conditions for an solution to exist. There can be solutions to an IVP even if the function <m>f(t,y)</m> isn't continuous.
                    <md>
                      y'=2\sqrt{y} \qquad y(0)=0
                    </md>
                     has a solution <m>y=t^2</m> even though <m>\sqrt{y}</m> is not continuous at <m>(0,0)</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The theorem is also true if there are more than one dependent variable and all the partial derivatives with respect to the dependent variables are continuous. For example, given the IVP
                    <md>
                      x'=f(t,x,y)\quad y'=g(t,x,y)\qquad x(t_0)=x_0\quad y(t_0)=y_0
                    </md>
                    then if <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are continuous at <m>(t_0,x_0,y_0)</m>  then a solution exists. If the partial derivatives <m>f_x,f_y,g_x,g_y</m> are also continuous then the solution is unique.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>
        <example>
          <p>
            Solve the differential equation
            <md>
              y'=-3t^2(y-2)^2
            </md>
            For the initial conditions
            <md>
             (a) \quad y(0)=3 \qquad(b) \quad y(0)=1 \qquad(c) \quad y(0)=2
            </md>
          </p>
          
          <p>
            Firstly <m>f=3t^2(y-2)^2</m> and <m>f_y=12t^2(y-2)</m> are continuous everywhere so a unique solution exists for any initial condition.
          </p>
          <p>  
            Separating the variables and integrating
            <md>
              \int \frac{dy}{(y-2)^2}=-\int 3t^2\,dt\quad\Rightarrow\quad \frac{1}{y-2}=t^3+c
            </md>
            <md>
              y=2+\frac{1}{c+t^3}
            </md>
            (a)
            <md>
              y(1)=3 =2+\frac{1}{c}\quad\Rightarrow\quad c=1\quad y(t)=2+\frac{1}{1+t^3}
            </md>
            (b)
            <md>
              y(1)=1 =2+\frac{1}{c}\quad\Rightarrow\quad c=-1\quad y(t)=2+\frac{1}{t^3-1}
            </md>
            (c)
            <md>
              y(2)=2 = 2+\frac{1}{c}\quad\Rightarrow\quad c=?
            </md>
            The problem goes back to separating the variables. If <m>y(0)=2</m>, dividing by <m>y-2</m> is not allowed. We know there is a unique solution from the theorem. Substituting <m>y(t)=2</m> into the differential equation shows that that is a solution. <m>y(t)=2</m> is an example of a singular or equilibrium solution
          </p>
        </example>
        <example>
          <p>
            Consider IVPs associated with the differential equation
            <md>
              y'=2t\sqrt{1-y^2}
            </md>
            Clearly if <m>y_0^2\gt 1 </m> the solutions will not exist. For <m>|y|\lt 1</m>, <m>f=2t\sqrt{1-y^2}</m> is continuous and <m>y=\pm 1</m> are singular solutions, so a solution will exist for <m>-1\leq y_0\leq 1</m>. For <m>|y|\lt 1</m> the partial derivative <m>f_y=-2ty/\sqrt{1-y^2}</m> is continuous, but <m>f_y</m> is undefined at <m>y=\pm 1</m>. So there is a possibility of non uniqueness at those <m>y</m> values.
           </p>
           <p>
            Separating the variables and integrating
            <md>
              \int\frac{dy}{\sqrt{1-y^2}}=\int 2t\,dt\quad\Rightarrow\quad \sin^{-1}y=t^2+c
            </md>
            Incorporating the initial condition gives
            <md>
              y=\sin (t^2-t_0^2+\sin^{-1}y_0)
            </md>
            For <m>y_0=1</m> this becomes
            <md>
              y=\sin\left(t^2-t_0^2+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)
            </md>
            But <m>y=1</m> is also a solution so there are at least two solutions hence non uniqueness.
           </p>
           <p>
            The situation is actually worse. There are an infinite number of solutions. If <m>y_0=1,t\lt 0</m>, <m>f=2t\sqrt{1-y^2}</m> is negative so there is a choice between the singular solution and the sinusoidal solution. If <m>y_0=-1</m> the only possibility is the singular solution. For <m>t\gt 0</m> the situation is reversed, for <m>y_0=1</m> there is only the singular solution and for <m>y_0=-1</m> there is a choice. Some of the possible solutions for the initial condition <m>y(-2)=1</m>are graphed below.
            <image source="Nonunique.png" width="60%">
              <shortdescription>(for accessibility)</shortdescription>
            </image>
           </p>
        </example>
      </section>
      
      
    </chapter>

   
   
